gs together into a coherent methodological framework the thought of such diverse thinkers as Weber, Wittgenstein, and Nietzsche. In a contemporary intellectual context that celebrates difference and cultural relativism, this book makes a case for disciplined comparison, a humane view of human nature, and a theoretical understanding of "family resemblances" and differences across great cultural divides.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCannibalism. 0aEthnology. 0aReincarnationvComparative studies. 0aReincarnationxBuddhism. 0aReincarnationxComparative studies. 0aReligious ethicsvComparative studies. 0aReligious ethicsxComparative studies. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh  aamerindian tradition.  abuddhism.  abuddhist tradition.  acanada.  aclassicists.  acosmology.  across cultural scholarship.  acultural relativism.  acultural stories.  adeath.  aempedocles.  aethics.  agreek tradition.  ahuman condition.  aindic civilizations.  aindologists.  aintellectual context.  akarma.  amelanesia.  amethodological framework.  anietzsche.  apersonal transformation.  aphilosophy.  apindar.  aplato.  apythagoras.  arebirth.  areincarnation.  asiberia.  atextbooks.  aweber.  awest africa.  awittgenstein.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093630040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936300423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936300/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles